You can differentiate between null and empty list by making the parameter optional. Setting [RequestParam.required][1] to false will do the trick.

&gt; Switch this to false if you prefer a null value if the parameter is not present in the request.

Simplified example for testing:
```
@GetMapping(&quot;/test&quot;)
public ResponseEntity&lt;Object&gt; test(@RequestParam(required = false) List&lt;String&gt; list) {
  if (list == null) {
    return ResponseEntity.ok(&quot;Null&quot;);
  }
  if (list.isEmpty()) {
    return ResponseEntity.ok(&quot;Empty&quot;);
  }
  return ResponseEntity.ok(&quot;Has Values&quot;);
}
```
Calling the url without the parameter, `/test`, will make list `null`.

Calling with parameter present, but without values - `/test?list` or `/test?list=`, will make the list empty.

Calling with values - `/test?list=11,12`, makes the list to have values.

It was mentioned in comments, but i will mention it here as well - if at all possible, redesign the API. Clients tend to forget such minute details, and it will increase the workload on the support.

  [1]: https://docs.spring.io/spring-framework/docs/current/javadoc-api/org/springframework/web/bind/annotation/RequestParam.html#required()

